ered them international economic, military, and political support. Though now well-positioned to function as an independent state, Iraqi Kurdistan has vacillated in seizing this golden opportunity to declare independence. The apparent Kurdish willingness to forgo independence runs counter to the prevailing narratives about the Kurds in the Middle East. Hassan draws not only on the history of the Kurds but also on first-hand interviews with high-ranking officials, journalists, and nationalists to provide a new window into the calculations of Kurdish leaders as they navigate the complicated politics of Iraq. Secession and Conflict offers a new model for understanding the Kurdish question in Iraq.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAutonomy and independence movementsxHistory. 0aAutonomy and independence movements. 0aKurdszIraqxPolitics and governmenty21st century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / General.2bisacsh  aAmerica.  aConflict.  aIran.  aIraq.  aIraqi Kurdistan.  aKosovo.  aKurdish.  aMiddle East.  aSouth Sudan.  aSyria.  aTurkey.  acomparative politics.  aconstructivism.  ademocracy.  adiplomacy.  aethnic conflict.  afederalism.  aindependence.  ainternational relations.  aliberalism.  amultiethnic state.  anationalism.  arealism.  areferendum.  asecession.  astate building.  awar.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228015246?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228015246423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228015246/original  a978-3-11-127195-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-1